spec: socket_extra152
version: ">=3.9"
backend: python_module(socket)

docs: https://docs.python.org/3/library/socket.html

provenance:
  derived_from:
    - "https://docs.python.org/3/library/socket.html — Python socket module documentation"
    - "Test vectors verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11"
  not_derived_from:
    - "CPython source: Lib/socket.py"
    - "CPython source: Modules/socketmodule.c"
    - "socket_extra151.zspec.zsdl — covers socket.AF_INET.__eq__(2) / AF_INET6.__eq__(30) / AF_UNIX.__eq__(1) / SOCK_STREAM.__eq__(1) / SOCK_DGRAM.__eq__(2) / AF_* and SOCK_* class names (table + invariants)."
    - "socket_extra150.zspec.zsdl — covers _socket.__dict__.__len__()==235 / _socket.__dict__.__class__.__name__.__eq__('dict') / _socket.__dict__.__contains__('socket'/'AF_INET'/'IPPROTO_TCP'/'SO_REUSEADDR'/'gethostname'/'getaddrinfo'/'gethostbyname'/'inet_aton') / _socket.socket.__dict__.__len__()==37 (table + invariants)."
    - "socket_extra149.zspec.zsdl — covers socket.__dict__.__len__()==267 / socket.socket.__dict__.__len__()==28 / socket.AddressFamily.__dict__.__len__()==25 / socket.SocketKind.__dict__.__len__()==20 (table + invariants)."
    - "socket_extra144.zspec.zsdl — covers socket.socket.__module__/__qualname__/__eq__('socket') / socket.socket.__dict__.__class__.__name__.__eq__('mappingproxy') / __mro__.__len__()==3 (table + invariants)."
    - "socket_extra142.zspec.zsdl — covers socket.AF_INET/AF_INET6 enum member .name values / SOCK_STREAM/SOCK_DGRAM .name values / AddressFamily/SocketKind class __name__ values (table + invariants)."
    - "socket.zspec / early extras — cover socket.__name__/__package__ (base spec)."
  notes:
    - "This spec does NOT duplicate invariants present in socket_extra93 through socket_extra151."
    - "Wave 334 theme: socket.socket class identity and method qualnames — socket.socket.__name__.__eq__('socket') / socket.__module__.__eq__('socket') / socket.__bases__[0].__name__.__eq__('socket') (base is _socket.socket) / socket.socket.connect.__qualname__.__eq__('socket.connect') / socket.socket.bind.__qualname__.__eq__('socket.bind') / socket.socket.listen.__qualname__.__eq__('socket.listen') / socket.error.__name__.__eq__('OSError') / socket.gaierror.__name__.__eq__('gaierror') / socket.gaierror.__module__.__eq__('socket')."
    - "socket.socket.__name__ == 'socket'. Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0."
    - "socket.socket.__module__ == 'socket'. Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0."
    - "socket.socket.__bases__[0].__name__ == 'socket'. Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0."
    - "socket.socket.__bases__[0].__module__ == '_socket'. Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0."
    - "socket.socket.connect.__qualname__ == 'socket.connect'. Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0."
    - "socket.socket.bind.__qualname__ == 'socket.bind'. Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0."
    - "socket.socket.listen.__qualname__ == 'socket.listen'. Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0."
    - "socket.error.__name__ == 'OSError'. Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0."
    - "socket.gaierror.__name__ == 'gaierror'. Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0."
    - "socket.gaierror.__module__ == 'socket'. Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0."
    - "Note: socket.socket.__bases__[0].__name__ == 'socket'. The Python-level socket.socket class inherits from the C extension type _socket.socket, which also has __name__ == 'socket'. Both the Python class and the C class share the name 'socket'. The distinguishing factor is their __module__: Python socket.socket.__module__ == 'socket' (6 chars, no underscore) while _socket.socket.__module__ == '_socket' (7 chars with underscore). The MRO of socket.socket is [socket.socket, _socket.socket, object] (3 elements, anchored by extra144). So socket.socket.__bases__[0].__name__=='socket' and socket.socket.__bases__[0].__module__=='_socket'."
    - "Note: socket.socket.connect.__qualname__ == 'socket.connect' (14 chars). This uses the class name 'socket' as prefix (not 'socket.socket'), because the qualname format for C extension methods is just 'ClassName.method_name' where ClassName is the __name__ of the C extension type (_socket.socket.__name__ == 'socket'). Similarly for bind ('socket.bind', 11 chars) and listen ('socket.listen', 13 chars). The 'socket.' prefix is 7 chars."
    - "Note: socket.error.__name__ == 'OSError' (7 chars). socket.error is an alias for OSError — it IS OSError, not a subclass. So socket.error.__name__ returns 'OSError', not 'error'. This differs from struct.error where __name__ == 'error' (lowercase, 5 chars). socket.error is used for backward compatibility; modern code should catch OSError directly."
    - "Note: socket.gaierror.__name__ == 'gaierror' (8 chars). socket.gaierror is a proper subclass of OSError (and socket.error). Its __name__ is 'gaierror' (lowercase, like struct.error), not 'GAIError' or similar. It is raised by getaddrinfo and related DNS resolution functions when address info cannot be resolved. Its __module__ is 'socket' (6 chars)."
    - "All expected values verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11."
  created_at: "2026-04-11T00:00:00Z"

error_model: python_exceptions

